<DOC><DOCNO> AP881205-0156 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1925EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--JudicialStrike     12-05 0136</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Judicial Strike,0140</SECOND><HEAD>Justice Strike Paralyzes Portugal's Courts</HEAD><DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Judges went on strike Monday, paralyzingthe court system, and other unions announced protests that coulddisrupt trials for two weeks.   The Union of Judicial Magistrates called the three-day strikeafter the government included Portugal's 1,200 judges in a salaryrestructuring plan for public employees. The union claims the movewill lead to lower pay rises.   Other court officials have planned a one-day strike Friday whilepublic prosecutors have anounced they will stop work for three daysnext week.   This week's action is the first ever national strike byPortuguese judges.   Courts are running only a minimum service to handle cases wherethe liberty of individuals is at stake.   Trade union estimates said 90 percent of the judges had acceptedthe strike call.</TEXT></DOC>